================================================================================
PART 1: OAUTH 2.0 INTRODUCTION
================================================================================

1. OAuth 2.0 Kya Hai?
---------------------
- OAuth 2.0 ek **Authorization Framework** hai.
- Ye ek application ko doosri application ka data access karne ki permission deta hai.
- **Bina password share kiye.**
- Example: "Login with Google" button.

2. OAuth 2.0 Ki Zaroorat Kyun Padi?
-----------------------------------
- Purane tarike mein user apna Google password third-party app ko deta tha (Security Risk).
- OAuth 2.0 mein third-party app ko **Token** milta hai, password nahi.
- Token limited access deta hai aur expire ho jata hai.

3. Real Life Analogy (Hotel Room Key)
-------------------------------------
- Bina OAuth: Receptionist tumhara ghar ka main gate ka key maang leta hai. (Risk)
- OAuth Ke Saath: Receptionist tumhe ek **Card Key** deta hai jo sirf ek room kholega, 2 din ke liye. (Safe)

================================================================================
PART 2: OAUTH 2.0 ROLES (4 MAIN CHARACTERS)
================================================================================

| Role | Naam | Kaam | Example |
|:-----|:-----|:-----|:--------|
| 1 | Resource Owner | Jiska data hai | User (Tum) |
| 2 | Client | Data maangne wala app | mycoolapp.com |
| 3 | Authorization Server | Token dene wala | Google / Keycloak |
| 4 | Resource Server | Jahan data rakha hai | Google Contacts API |

================================================================================
PART 3: OAUTH 2.0 GRANT TYPES (FLOWS)
================================================================================

1. Authorization Code Flow (Most Common & Secure)
-------------------------------------------------
- Use Case: Web Applications with Backend (React + Spring Boot).
- Security: Token directly Backend ko milta hai, Browser mein expose nahi hota.
- PKCE: Mobile/SPA ke liye enhanced security (Proof Key for Code Exchange).

2. Client Credentials Flow (Server-to-Server)
---------------------------------------------
- Use Case: Microservices communication, Cron Jobs.
- No User Involved.
- Service A sends client_id + client_secret → Gets Token → Calls Service B.

3. Device Authorization Flow (Input Limited Devices)
----------------------------------------------------
- Use Case: Apple TV, YouTube on Smart TV, CLI tools.
- Device shows a Code on screen.
- User enters Code on Phone/Laptop browser.
- Device keeps polling until approved.

4. Implicit Flow (⚠️ DEPRECATED)
-------------------------------
- Old way for SPAs. Token in URL Fragment.
- Insecure. Use Authorization Code + PKCE instead.

================================================================================
PART 4: TOKENS DEEP DIVE
================================================================================

1. Access Token
---------------
- Format: Usually JWT.
- Lifetime: Short-lived (5 min - 1 hour).
- Usage: Sent in `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header.
- Storage: Client side (LocalStorage/Memory). Server stateless.

2. Refresh Token
----------------
- Purpose: Get new Access Token without user re-login.
- Lifetime: Long-lived (Days/Weeks).
- Storage: Backend must store in Database (hashed).

3. ID Token (OpenID Connect)
----------------------------
- Purpose: Authentication (Login) ONLY, NOT for API access.
- Format: Always JWT.
- Contains: User identity (name, email, sub).

================================================================================
PART 5: OPENID CONNECT (OIDC)
================================================================================

- OAuth 2.0 = Authorization (Access Delegation).
- OIDC = Authentication (Identity) Layer on top of OAuth 2.0.
- OIDC adds `id_token` and `/userinfo` endpoint.

================================================================================
PART 6: KEYCLOAK - INTRODUCTION
================================================================================

1. Keycloak Kya Hai?
--------------------
- Open Source **Identity and Access Management (IAM)** tool.
- Works as Authorization Server (OAuth 2.0 / OIDC).
- Features: Single Sign-On (SSO), Social Login, User Federation (LDAP/AD).

2. Keycloak Components (Yaad Rakhne Layak)
------------------------------------------
| Component | Kaam |
|:----------|:-----|
| Realm | Tenant (Alag duniya). Isolates users, clients, roles. |
| Client | Tumhara Application (Spring Boot, React). |
| User | End User. |
| Role | Permission. (Realm Role = Global, Client Role = App-specific). |
| Group | Users ka collection. Group ko role assign kar sakte ho. |

================================================================================
PART 7: KEYCLOAK ENDPOINTS (BACKEND KE LIYE)
================================================================================

Base URL: http://localhost:8181/realms/{realm-name}

| Endpoint | Path | Kaam |
|:---------|:-----|:-----|
| Discovery | `/.well-known/openid-configuration` | Metadata (Saare endpoints) |
| Authorization | `/protocol/openid-connect/auth` | Login page URL |
| Token | `/protocol/openid-connect/token` | Code exchange for Token |
| JWKS | `/protocol/openid-connect/certs` | Public Keys (Signature verify) |
| User Info | `/protocol/openid-connect/userinfo` | User profile data |
| Introspect | `/protocol/openid-connect/token/introspect` | Opaque token validation |
| Logout | `/protocol/openid-connect/logout` | SSO session end |

